## **6. Findings and Results**

- **Finding 1:** `useradd` successfully created all six user accounts; each new user appeared in `/etc/passwd` confirming the accounts were added to the system identity database
- **Finding 2:** `cat /etc/passwd | cut -d: -f1` efficiently extracted only the username field (field 1, colon-delimited) from the full `/etc/passwd` records, demonstrating the power of piping and `cut` for structured text processing
- **Finding 3:** `usermod -a -G` with comma-separated group names added `arosalez` to `Sales`, `Managers`, and `Personnel` in a single command; the `-a` flag (append) prevented existing group memberships from being overwritten
- **Finding 4:** `groups arosalez` confirmed membership in all three assigned groups plus the default primary group, validating correct multi-group assignment
- **Finding 5:** When operating as `arosalez` (via `su`), `sudo touch myFile.txt` produced the expected "not in the sudoers file" message, confirming that sudo access is explicitly granted and not inherited from general user creation
- **Finding 6:** `sudo journalctl | grep "user NOT in sudoers"` successfully located the audit log entry recording `arosalez`'s denied sudo attempt, including the exact timestamp and attempted command
- **Finding 7:** The `su` command allowed identity switching without logging out of the `ssm-user` session, enabling testing of user-specific permissions within a single terminal session

